%I A396265 #10 Jun 06 2026 03:29:16
%S A396265 10,15,18,20,21,22,26,28,30,33,34,35,36,38,40,42,44,45,46,48,50,51,52,
%T A396265 54,55,56,57,58,60,63,65,66,68,69,70,72,74,75,76,77,78,80,82,84,85,86,
%U A396265 87,88,90,91,92,93,94,95,96,98,99,100,102,104,105,106,108,110
%N A396265 Numbers k such that there exists a number r < k such that both gcd(r,k) > 1 and rad(r) does not divide k, yet rad(r+m*k) | k for some m, where rad = A007947.
%C A396265 Numbers k such that there exists a number r in row k of A272619 (i.e., [1..k] \ union({row k of A038566}, {row k of A162306})) such that rad(r+m*k) | k for some m >= 0.
%C A396265 Powers of primes p^m, m >= 0 (p^m in A000961) are such that row p^m of A272619 and row p^m of A381801 do not intersect.
%C A396265 This sequence is A024619 \ A382438.
%C A396265 Conjecture: includes A126706 \ {12, 24}.
%H A396265 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A396265/b396265.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A396265 Let s = r + m * k.
%e A396265 6 is not in this sequence since r < 6 is either coprime to 6 or rad(r) | 6.
%e A396265 10 is in this sequence since for r = 6 and s = 16 = 6+1*10, rad(16) | 10, while gcd(6,10)=2 and rad(6) does not divide 10.
%e A396265 12 is not in this sequence since row 12 of A038566 is {1, 5, 7, 11} and row 12 of A162306 is {1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9}, leaving 10 in row 12 of A272619. However, numbers congruent to 10 (mod 12) are not divisible by 3. Therefore there does not exist a number r such that rad(r+12*m) | 12 for some m >= 0.
%e A396265 14 is not in this sequence since row 14 of A272619 is {6, 10, 12}, and the prime power residues of 2 (mod 14) are {1,2,4,8} and of 7 are {1,7}, thus row 14 of A381801 is {0, 1, 2, 4, 7, 8}; these sets are disjoint. Therefore there does not exist a number r such that rad(r+12*m) | 12 for some m >= 0.
%e A396265 15 is in this sequence since row 15 of A272619 = {6, 10, 12} and row 15 of A381801 = {0, 1, 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, 12} intersect, etc.
%t A396265 nn = 120; rad[x_] := Times @@ FactorInteger[x][[All, 1]];
%t A396265 a382438[x_] := Module[{p}, Union@ Flatten@ Mod[TensorProduct @@ Map[(p = #; NestWhileList[Mod[p*#, x] &, 1, UnsameQ, All]) &, FactorInteger[x][[All, 1]] ], x] ];
%t A396265 a024619 = Select[Range[2, nn], Not @* PrimePowerQ];
%t A396265 Select[a024619, Function[k, ! AllTrue[Rest@ a382438[k], Divisible[k, rad[#] ] &] ] ]
%Y A396265 Cf. A000961, A007947, A024619, A038566, A126706, A162306, A272619, A381800, A381801, A381804, A382438.
%K A396265 nonn,changed
%O A396265 1,1
%A A396265 _Michael De Vlieger_, May 21 2026
